I'm not sure if this has affected others but I keep running into the static middleware handling my `index.html` and it not getting passed through to the router. Here's my code:

```
var express = require('express'),
    cons = require('consolidate'),
    port = process.argv[2] || 8080,
    app = express();

app.engine('html', cons.hogan);
app.set('view engine', 'html');
app.set('views', __dirname);

app.configure(function() {
  app.use(express['static'](__dirname));
});

app.get('/', function(req, res) {
  res.render('index', {
    hi : 'world'
  });
});

app.listen(port);
```

Now granted, this is for a quick server that I want to throw up to test something. But the problem is never immediately clear to me and I'm not sure that static should be handling `index.html` especially when it seems that express advocates overriding how html files are handled. 

Example (from consolidate readme):

```
// assign the swig engine to .html files
app.engine('html', cons.swig);
```

It's definitely a corner-case, but I don't really see the benefit of having static handle `index.html`, other than saving one route for static webpages. Unless it's for caching, but then maybe all html files should be handled by the static  middleware and `app.engine('html', ...)` isn't recommended.

